WEBVTT

00:01.001 --> 00:03.337
‐ Richard, you
vastly overspent,

00:03.337 --> 00:05.756
and it's not unreasonable
that we would be upset.

00:05.756 --> 00:07.925
‐ It'll work.
I promise you.

00:07.925 --> 00:10.052
‐ The FDA created
a special label

00:10.052 --> 00:12.095
to say that
it's less addictive.

00:12.095 --> 00:14.765
‐ I would never prescribe
a narcotic for moderate pain.

00:14.765 --> 00:16.266
‐ That fucking label
caused everything.

00:16.266 --> 00:19.061
This drug has only been
on the market for three years,

00:19.061 --> 00:21.605
and there's already
been a spike in overdoses.

00:21.605 --> 00:23.649
‐ Our community is ground zero

00:23.649 --> 00:25.692
for a growing
national catastrophe.

00:25.692 --> 00:27.402
‐ We're gonna do
everything we can

00:27.402 --> 00:28.487
to hold someone accountable.

00:28.487 --> 00:29.905
But you got all these people.

00:29.905 --> 00:32.241
They almost never mention
OxyContin by name

00:32.241 --> 00:33.700
in the video
promoting OxyContin.

00:33.700 --> 00:34.952
RANDY: And this video is

00:34.952 --> 00:36.370
the first major introduction
of OxyContin.

00:36.370 --> 00:38.330
‐ Prove they're lying
about the dangers of the drug

00:38.330 --> 00:39.665
and that they're
selling it anyway.

00:39.665 --> 00:40.916
‐ I can't lose my job.

00:40.916 --> 00:42.459
I gotta make enough money
to get out of here.

00:42.459 --> 00:45.462
‐ There's a new drug.
The FDA said it's safe.

00:47.923 --> 00:50.926
[tense music]

00:50.926 --> 00:57.558
♪ ♪

00:57.558 --> 01:00.060
‐ Do you solemnly swear that
you will correctly transcribe

01:00.060 --> 01:02.646
to the best of your ability
all of the testimony

01:02.646 --> 01:05.107
given by each and every witness
testifying in the matter

01:05.107 --> 01:06.984
now pending
before this grand jury

01:06.984 --> 01:09.486
and that you will keep secret
and divulge to no one

01:09.486 --> 01:12.614
any of the proceedings of this
grand jury, so help you God?

01:12.614 --> 01:13.615
‐ I do.

01:13.615 --> 01:16.618
[dramatic music]

01:16.618 --> 01:23.625
♪ ♪

01:27.462 --> 01:30.257
PROFESSOR: It takes
10 to 15 years for a new drug

01:30.257 --> 01:32.884
to complete the journey from
inception to the marketplace.

01:32.884 --> 01:39.891
♪ ♪

01:45.439 --> 01:49.610
‐ If OxyContin had failed
when it launched in 1996,

01:49.610 --> 01:51.153
what would have been
the consequences?

01:51.153 --> 01:53.739
‐ Purdue Pharma
would have lost $40 million

01:53.739 --> 01:56.074
with no significant product
in the pipeline.

01:58.118 --> 01:59.995
BETH: Big day, right?

01:59.995 --> 02:02.080
First sets of numbers
coming in?

02:03.206 --> 02:05.792
‐ I'm sure they'll be fine.

02:05.792 --> 02:12.758
♪ ♪

02:23.268 --> 02:25.228
‐ And how much damage
would that have inflicted

02:25.228 --> 02:26.313
on Purdue Pharma?

02:26.313 --> 02:27.606
‐ It likely would have

02:27.606 --> 02:29.191
sunk the entire company.

02:33.904 --> 02:35.405
‐ They're not bad.

02:35.405 --> 02:36.740
‐ We can do better.

02:37.824 --> 02:40.160
How's our video
testimonial coming?

02:40.160 --> 02:41.161
MICHAEL: A bit slow.

02:41.161 --> 02:42.162
The drug is so new,

02:42.162 --> 02:43.330
there's not a lot of people

02:43.330 --> 02:45.040
who can testify to it
at this point.

02:45.040 --> 02:47.250
‐ Then find some.
‐ Yes, sir.

02:47.250 --> 02:48.543
RICHARD:
Physicians need to know

02:48.543 --> 02:51.463
it can take its place
next to penicillin

02:51.463 --> 02:55.133
as one of the most important
in the history of medicine.

02:55.133 --> 02:57.969
Let's hold
more weekend seminars

02:57.969 --> 03:00.263
to explain to physicians

03:00.263 --> 03:03.100
how truly revolutionary
this drug is.

03:05.977 --> 03:08.021
‐ It's your favorite
pharma rep.

03:08.021 --> 03:09.648
‐ If he's gonna bribe you
for access,

03:09.648 --> 03:11.149
you should get
more than flowers.

03:11.149 --> 03:12.567
‐ How about a mani‐pedi
next time?

03:12.567 --> 03:14.778
‐ Yes, please.

03:14.778 --> 03:16.363
‐ And your present, Doc,

03:16.363 --> 03:19.616
is a pen
with a titration chart in it.

03:19.616 --> 03:20.951
‐ Oh.
‐ There you go.

03:20.951 --> 03:22.202
‐ Thanks.

03:22.202 --> 03:25.163
Think I'd rather have flowers.
‐ [laughs]

03:25.163 --> 03:26.873
So now that you bought
your way into my office,

03:26.873 --> 03:27.958
what do you need?

03:27.958 --> 03:30.210
‐ Can we sit for a minute?
‐ Sure.

03:30.210 --> 03:36.299
‐ I wanted to extend an
exciting invitation your way.

03:36.299 --> 03:41.012
Purdue want to invite you
to an all‐expenses paid trip

03:41.012 --> 03:44.266
to Scottsdale, Arizona,
at a five‐star resort

03:44.266 --> 03:47.269
to hear pain experts
discuss new treatments.

03:47.269 --> 03:49.771
‐ Even allowed to do that?
Isn't it illegal or something?

03:49.771 --> 03:52.566
‐ Oh, you kidding me?
No, it absolutely is.

03:52.566 --> 03:55.861
All the pharmas do it,
and, you know, these seminars,

03:55.861 --> 03:58.530
they're a lot of fun,
and they're very informative.

03:58.530 --> 04:00.073
‐ Mm.
I can't.

04:00.073 --> 04:01.783
I've got‐‐I've got
a full practice,

04:01.783 --> 04:03.118
even on weekends.

04:03.118 --> 04:04.327
Too many folks.
‐ Right.

04:04.327 --> 04:05.662
But the seminar

04:05.662 --> 04:08.081
would be an extension
of your work here.

04:08.081 --> 04:09.541
There'll be a lot
of pain experts,

04:09.541 --> 04:11.543
and you'll walk away
with some great tips.

04:11.543 --> 04:13.336
Take your wife, you know?

04:13.336 --> 04:16.173
Two of you could have
a relaxing spa weekend.

04:16.173 --> 04:21.553
‐ My wife passed away
from ovarian cancer, so...

04:21.553 --> 04:22.637
‐ Oh, my God.
SAMUEL: Yeah.

04:22.637 --> 04:24.014
I'm sorry.
SAMUEL: Yeah.

04:24.014 --> 04:26.266
It's all right.
It's all right.

04:26.266 --> 04:29.519
‐ Well, um, I'll keep
checking in with you.

04:29.519 --> 04:32.731
And, uh...
think about Scottsdale.

04:33.523 --> 04:34.941
‐ [chuckling]
Sure.

04:34.941 --> 04:36.735
‐ It'll be fun, Doc.

04:39.905 --> 04:42.908
[tense music]

04:42.908 --> 04:48.538
♪ ♪

04:48.538 --> 04:49.664
‐ Hey, Logan.

04:49.664 --> 04:51.666
I've been wanting
to check on you.

04:51.666 --> 04:53.585
Wanna take a look
at that shoulder.

04:53.585 --> 04:55.045
LOGAN: Doing the same.

04:55.045 --> 04:58.757
Still can't lift it more‐‐
much more than that.

04:58.757 --> 05:00.717
Pains the shoulder
something awful.

05:00.717 --> 05:02.052
‐ Yeah.

05:02.052 --> 05:03.345
LOGAN:
Been more than six years, Doc.

05:03.345 --> 05:06.389
‐ Yeah, I know.
I know.

05:07.516 --> 05:11.686
Hey, there's a new medication
I might want you to try.

05:12.604 --> 05:14.606
‐ What kind
of medication's that?

05:14.606 --> 05:16.441
‐ When a patient
first takes OxyContin,

05:16.441 --> 05:18.235
it can be very effective.

05:19.861 --> 05:21.238
The patient often feels like

05:21.238 --> 05:23.615
their life has been
instantly transformed.

05:23.615 --> 05:26.326
[banging]

05:26.326 --> 05:29.371
Unfortunately, the drug didn't
always work as Purdue claimed.

05:29.371 --> 05:31.164
‐ Oh, how so?

05:31.164 --> 05:35.377
‐ [groaning]

05:35.377 --> 05:37.921
♪ ♪

05:37.921 --> 05:40.215
‐ So we've been getting some
complaints from patients

05:40.215 --> 05:44.594
and doctors that the drug
isn't lasting 12 hours.

05:44.594 --> 05:45.720
People are waking up

05:45.720 --> 05:47.722
in the middle of the night
in pain.

05:47.722 --> 05:50.559
‐ Our entire FDA approval
is based on the fact

05:50.559 --> 05:52.310
that it's a 12‐hour drug.

05:52.310 --> 05:54.563
Insurance companies
and hospitals won't cover it

05:54.563 --> 05:57.774
if it doesn't last
the full 12 hours.

05:57.774 --> 05:59.025
How did this happen?

05:59.025 --> 06:00.777
‐ Well, we always knew
it was a possibility

06:00.777 --> 06:03.113
that the drug
wouldn't last 12 hours.

06:03.113 --> 06:05.615
The Puerto Rico testing
only hit at 50%‐‐

06:05.615 --> 06:09.786
‐ The FDA only requires
a 50% threshold.

06:11.997 --> 06:12.998
Thank you.

06:12.998 --> 06:14.332
That will be all.

06:17.627 --> 06:20.630
[soft tense music]

06:20.630 --> 06:27.637
♪ ♪

06:28.054 --> 06:29.389
Don't worry.

06:29.389 --> 06:31.099
We'll figure this out.

06:31.099 --> 06:32.809
It's an excellent drug.

06:32.809 --> 06:38.982
♪ ♪

06:38.982 --> 06:40.358
[door shuts]

06:40.358 --> 06:42.068
PERSON: You've got
your mother worried sick

06:42.068 --> 06:43.695
about you, Richie.

06:45.196 --> 06:46.698
‐ Well, our patent expired.

06:46.698 --> 06:49.367
Dad would be dead
without a replacement.

06:49.367 --> 06:52.370
‐ Because ear wax just isn't
good enough for you.

06:54.080 --> 06:56.917
‐ Forgive me for trying to...

06:56.917 --> 06:59.920
make us more
than the Betadine family.

06:59.920 --> 07:04.716
‐ I know, I know,
you've got grand ambitions,

07:04.716 --> 07:08.178
but I am concerned
you're going to become Icarus.

07:08.178 --> 07:11.973
♪ ♪

07:11.973 --> 07:16.269
‐ If OxyContin does
what I think it can,

07:16.269 --> 07:17.479
then it's gonna be bigger

07:17.479 --> 07:19.648
than anything Uncle Arthur
ever dreamed.

07:19.648 --> 07:21.399
[eerie music]

07:21.399 --> 07:24.069
‐ Richie...

07:24.069 --> 07:25.654
Arthur is dead.

07:25.654 --> 07:32.661
♪ ♪

07:35.580 --> 07:39.876
‐ When Roche hired Arthur
Sackler to market value,

07:39.876 --> 07:42.379
he needed to find a way
to separate it from Librium.

07:42.379 --> 07:49.010
So Arthur devised
a specific medical condition

07:49.010 --> 07:51.972
called psychic tension.

07:51.972 --> 07:54.265
Where Librium
was taken for anxiety,

07:54.265 --> 07:56.893
you would need
a much stronger medication

07:56.893 --> 07:59.854
for psychic tension.

07:59.854 --> 08:02.565
And thus, Valium became

08:02.565 --> 08:06.319
the number one tranquilizer
on the market

08:06.319 --> 08:12.951
by creating the condition
known as psychic tension.

08:17.414 --> 08:22.043
Now, we have created
the greatest painkiller

08:22.043 --> 08:26.423
in the history
of human civilization...

08:26.423 --> 08:31.928
and all we have to do
to ensure the world gets it

08:31.928 --> 08:34.806
is to figure out
a medical condition

08:34.806 --> 08:40.603
that would require
an OxyContin patient...

08:40.603 --> 08:42.564
to double their dose.

08:42.564 --> 08:47.027
♪ ♪

08:47.027 --> 08:49.279
MARTIN: Today we're gonna talk
about a medical condition

08:49.279 --> 08:51.781
known as breakthrough pain.

08:51.781 --> 08:53.033
Neither common nor rare,

08:53.033 --> 08:56.244
breakthrough pain
is a specific type of pain

08:56.244 --> 08:58.663
that breaks through
the 12‐hour cycle.

08:58.663 --> 09:00.915
‐ Yeah, I've had
several complaints‐‐

09:00.915 --> 09:02.625
or should I say questions‐‐

09:02.625 --> 09:04.627
about the drug
not lasting 12 hours.

09:04.627 --> 09:06.755
‐ All right,
what you need to do

09:06.755 --> 09:10.050
is tell your doctors
that their patients

09:10.050 --> 09:12.093
are experiencing
breakthrough pain.

09:12.093 --> 09:14.471
But we have
an effective solution

09:14.471 --> 09:16.056
that will allow their patients

09:16.056 --> 09:19.517
to get a full night's sleep
on OxyContin.

09:19.517 --> 09:22.228
All they have to do
is double the dose.

09:22.228 --> 09:25.231
So if they are
on 10 milligrams,

09:25.231 --> 09:27.984
they double the dose to 20.

09:27.984 --> 09:31.821
If they're already on 20,
they double to 40.

09:31.821 --> 09:34.991
♪ ♪

09:34.991 --> 09:37.994
[indistinct chatter]

09:39.412 --> 09:42.457
‐ Hey, if this drug
isn't working

09:42.457 --> 09:44.292
like we say it is,

09:44.292 --> 09:45.960
doctors are gonna stop
prescribing it.

09:47.712 --> 09:49.839
‐ Then maybe you should start
selling Viagra.

09:49.839 --> 09:51.925
‐ Thanks for the help.

09:51.925 --> 09:54.928
‐ Look, the 20
and 40 milligrams

09:54.928 --> 09:57.388
are two and four times
more expensive than the 10.

09:57.388 --> 10:00.308
So if we can convince doctors
to double their doses,

10:00.308 --> 10:02.102
we will be doubling
our paychecks.

10:02.102 --> 10:05.146
‐ Yeah, I get that, but...

10:05.146 --> 10:06.648
what if it doesn't work?

10:06.648 --> 10:10.068
‐ No drug is going to work
perfectly for every patient,

10:10.068 --> 10:12.070
and that's not our problem.

10:12.070 --> 10:13.905
Our job is to sell.
‐ [scoffs]

10:16.199 --> 10:17.575
Then I guess
we double the dose.

10:17.575 --> 10:19.369
‐ Yeah.

10:19.369 --> 10:21.746
‐ Doc, I was able
to get some information

10:21.746 --> 10:23.748
on the 12‐hour issue,

10:23.748 --> 10:25.959
and, uh, it's not uncommon.

10:25.959 --> 10:27.418
What your patient's
experiencing

10:27.418 --> 10:29.212
is breakthrough pain,

10:29.212 --> 10:31.881
and it can happen
hours nine and ten,

10:31.881 --> 10:34.259
especially if the pain
is uniquely acute.

10:34.259 --> 10:35.510
‐ Breakthrough pain.

10:35.510 --> 10:37.095
I've never heard
of breakthrough pain.

10:37.095 --> 10:38.179
BILLY: You really haven't?

10:38.179 --> 10:40.849
Well, it's a‐‐it's a term used

10:40.849 --> 10:45.645
primarily by, uh‐‐
by pain specialists, you know?

10:45.645 --> 10:47.480
And the solution is‐‐is simple.

10:47.480 --> 10:50.817
You, uh‐‐you
just double the dose.

10:50.817 --> 10:52.944
So if they're on 10 milligrams,

10:52.944 --> 10:54.195
you know,
you bump them up to 20.

10:54.195 --> 10:55.572
‐ Oh, no, no, no.

10:55.572 --> 10:57.907
No, that's‐‐that's too strong
for a narcotic.

10:57.907 --> 10:59.367
I'll just switch her
to Percocet

10:59.367 --> 11:02.162
or low‐dose morphine pills.

11:02.162 --> 11:04.205
‐ Doc, I wouldn't do that.

11:04.205 --> 11:07.500
Tho‐‐those drugs,
you know, they're not‐‐

11:07.500 --> 11:11.546
they're not non‐addictive
in the way that‐‐that OC is.

11:11.546 --> 11:13.882
And it's perfectly safe
to‐‐to double the dose.

11:13.882 --> 11:15.592
‐ You're telling me
that your drug

11:15.592 --> 11:19.345
is the only drug in the world
that can help my patients?

11:19.345 --> 11:21.723
BILLY: Well, ye‐‐I mean,
I'm saying‐‐

11:21.723 --> 11:25.059
I'm saying it's
your best option, you know?

11:25.059 --> 11:26.352
Have you had
a number of patients

11:26.352 --> 11:28.021
with‐‐with breakthrough
pain issues?

11:28.021 --> 11:30.940
‐ Well, I guess I just got one.

11:30.940 --> 11:33.234
I don't know, I've only got
four people on it, Billy.

11:33.234 --> 11:35.445
‐ Right, but they're all
doing great, right?

11:35.445 --> 11:37.864
‐ Yeah, it's been
very effective, actually.

11:37.864 --> 11:39.324
BILLY: See?
There you go.

11:39.324 --> 11:41.826
I‐‐I'd stay away
from morphine, Doc.

11:41.826 --> 11:45.079
You know, it's not, uh,
it's not 1894 anymore.

11:45.079 --> 11:47.540
Teddy Roosevelt
isn't president.

11:47.540 --> 11:50.501
‐ Well, Teddy Roosevelt
wasn't president then either,

11:50.501 --> 11:52.670
but I get your point.

11:52.670 --> 11:56.341
Uh, okay.

11:56.341 --> 11:59.219
Yeah, I guess morphine
would probably be too strong

11:59.219 --> 12:01.679
for her back injury anyway.

12:01.679 --> 12:06.059
♪ ♪

12:06.059 --> 12:08.353
Hello?

12:08.353 --> 12:09.771
‐ Uh, so‐‐sorry, Doc.

12:09.771 --> 12:11.940
I think you cut out there.

12:11.940 --> 12:14.150
I think doubling her up
to 20 milligrams

12:14.150 --> 12:15.151
will do the trick.

12:15.151 --> 12:16.694
Just‐‐just give it a try.

12:16.694 --> 12:18.154
All right, I'll let you go.

12:18.154 --> 12:19.155
Bye.

12:20.198 --> 12:23.701
MICHAEL: So, um,
there's a new issue.

12:24.494 --> 12:26.371
A number of doctors
have the misconception

12:26.371 --> 12:28.539
OxyContin is less powerful
than morphine,

12:28.539 --> 12:32.126
when, as you know, it's
much more powerful, and, uh,

12:32.126 --> 12:35.129
the confusion has started
to come up more frequently.

12:35.129 --> 12:36.589
RICK: What are some
of the side effects

12:36.589 --> 12:37.799
associated with morphine?

12:37.799 --> 12:39.884
‐ Difficulty breathing,

12:39.884 --> 12:43.012
sedation, coma, and death.

12:43.012 --> 12:46.557
‐ And is OxyContin
more potent than morphine?

12:46.557 --> 12:47.642
‐ Yes.

12:47.642 --> 12:49.560
Its active ingredient,
oxycodone,

12:49.560 --> 12:50.561
is twice as potent.

12:50.561 --> 12:52.188
‐ And thus twice as dangerous.

12:52.188 --> 12:54.399
‐ I think it would
be extremely dangerous

12:54.399 --> 12:56.776
at this early stage
in the life of this product

12:56.776 --> 12:59.779
to, um, clarify for physicians

12:59.779 --> 13:02.490
that our drug
is stronger than morphine.

13:02.490 --> 13:06.828
So we do not plan
to do anything about that.

13:06.828 --> 13:08.329
[dark music]

13:08.329 --> 13:10.748
‐ And I agree with you.

13:10.748 --> 13:12.750
‐ Well, you'll
be happy to know

13:12.750 --> 13:13.960
you're not the first person

13:13.960 --> 13:15.378
who can't sleep
through the night.

13:15.378 --> 13:17.547
That's not uncommon.

13:17.547 --> 13:20.717
So we've got two options.

13:20.717 --> 13:23.761
We can, uh, switch you
to a different medication.

13:23.761 --> 13:26.931
‐ No, I‐I don't wanna switch.

13:26.931 --> 13:29.642
This works better than anything
I've ever used before.

13:29.642 --> 13:32.895
‐ Okay, well, option two
is I can double your dose

13:32.895 --> 13:34.731
to 20 milligrams.

13:34.731 --> 13:37.525
But if that doesn't work,
we'll switch to something else.

13:38.234 --> 13:40.486
And if you're still having
a hard time

13:40.486 --> 13:42.488
sleeping through the night,
you call me.

13:42.488 --> 13:44.282
And if you don't call me,
girl...

13:45.116 --> 13:46.326
‐ Then you'll call me.

13:46.326 --> 13:47.410
‐ That's correct.

13:49.579 --> 13:54.334
So how's those moving plans
of yours coming along?

13:55.168 --> 13:57.920
‐ Uh, I don't know.

13:57.920 --> 14:00.673
Maybe I just keep my head down

14:00.673 --> 14:03.801
and figure it out
in a year or so.

14:07.138 --> 14:09.766
‐ You know,
when Shelly told me,

14:09.766 --> 14:13.186
"I want to move
to Finch Creek,"

14:13.186 --> 14:15.229
I thought, "Finch Creek?

14:15.229 --> 14:16.731
Are you nuts?
Finch Creek?"

14:16.731 --> 14:17.940
I mean,
I'm from this little town

14:17.940 --> 14:19.525
in southwest Pennsylvania.

14:19.525 --> 14:22.362
That's like New York City
compared to Finch Creek.

14:22.362 --> 14:25.323
I loved it
the minute I got here.

14:25.323 --> 14:28.451
Best decision I ever made.

14:28.451 --> 14:32.747
So if you wanna move
to Eureka Springs,

14:32.747 --> 14:34.624
you just go ahead
and dive in the deep end

14:34.624 --> 14:35.875
and do it.

14:35.875 --> 14:38.086
[tense music]

14:38.086 --> 14:39.921
All right?

14:39.921 --> 14:41.672
You can always come back.

14:41.672 --> 14:44.050
‐ Can I always move back?

14:44.050 --> 14:48.054
♪ ♪

14:48.054 --> 14:49.097
Thanks, Doc.

14:49.097 --> 14:50.598
‐ Bye.

14:50.598 --> 14:52.517
♪ ♪

