19:01.057 --> 19:02.767
PERSON: What do you want?

19:02.767 --> 19:05.478
‐ I'm Rick Mountcastle
with the federal government.

19:07.104 --> 19:09.023
[knocking]

19:10.816 --> 19:12.568
‐ Can I help you?
‐ Yes, ma'am.

19:12.568 --> 19:14.403
My name's Randy Ramseyer.

19:14.403 --> 19:15.446
I work for the government.

19:15.446 --> 19:16.614
‐ Why?
What's wrong?

19:21.243 --> 19:22.828
‐ So in the video you shot

19:22.828 --> 19:24.622
where you're taking
the medication OxyContin...

19:26.040 --> 19:30.294
‐ Yeah, I‐‐I was taking it
for a‐‐a injury.

19:30.294 --> 19:33.506
‐ And I noticed you‐‐you didn't
actually call it OxyContin.

19:33.506 --> 19:36.842
‐ I was told it was
a public service thing

19:36.842 --> 19:39.011
for chronic pain sufferers

19:39.011 --> 19:41.555
to be more comfortable
taking pain medication.

19:41.555 --> 19:43.265
Every now and then,
I would slip up,

19:43.265 --> 19:45.351
and I would say OxyContin.
‐ Well, yeah.

19:45.351 --> 19:46.769
‐ And they would say,
"Don't say that.

19:46.769 --> 19:48.521
Say 'the pain medicine.'"

19:48.521 --> 19:50.064
‐ Did the producer
ask you not to say

19:50.064 --> 19:53.442
the‐‐the name OxyContin?
‐ That's right.

19:53.442 --> 20:00.032
He‐‐he didn't want me to say
"opioid" or "opiates" either.

20:00.032 --> 20:03.661
‐ What'd he ask you to say?
‐ Uh, "medication."

20:03.661 --> 20:05.413
"Pain‐‐pain medication."

20:05.413 --> 20:06.956
RICK: Pain medication?
‐ Yeah.

20:06.956 --> 20:08.499
‐ But they told me
when I was done

20:08.499 --> 20:10.084
that I was real natural.

20:10.084 --> 20:12.169
‐ I can't imagine how hard
that would be,

20:12.169 --> 20:14.338
sitting in front of a camera
trying to be normal.

20:14.338 --> 20:16.048
[both laughing]

20:16.048 --> 20:18.718
‐ Oh, no.
He died a few years ago.

20:18.718 --> 20:20.803
Oh, I hate this gravel.

20:20.803 --> 20:22.430
‐ And was it drug‐related?

20:22.430 --> 20:25.266
‐ Oh, yeah, he was oxy‐cuted.

20:25.266 --> 20:26.892
‐ Who asked you to participate

20:26.892 --> 20:28.477
in the video
in the first place?

20:28.477 --> 20:31.105
‐ My doctor did,
Dr. Alan Spanos.

20:31.105 --> 20:34.191
‐ Oh, Alan Spanos.

20:34.191 --> 20:36.527
‐ Dr. Spanos.
Dr. Spanos.

20:36.527 --> 20:40.906
He‐‐he prescribed
OxyContin and...

20:40.906 --> 20:47.329
♪ ♪

20:47.329 --> 20:49.373
[mumbling]
Yeah, he...

20:51.959 --> 20:53.836
RICK: You all right?
PERSON: Uh‐huh.

20:53.836 --> 20:55.463
Yeah, yeah.

20:55.463 --> 20:57.339
Uh...

20:57.339 --> 21:04.180
♪ ♪

21:04.180 --> 21:06.182
RICK: And who reached out
to you initially?

21:06.974 --> 21:09.602
‐ It was an ad agency
from New York.

21:09.602 --> 21:10.978
‐ And when you were
approached,

21:10.978 --> 21:12.938
was it for a video
to promote OxyContin?

21:12.938 --> 21:15.816
‐ No, they said it was
a public service announcement

21:15.816 --> 21:20.154
for pain management
and general opioid use.

21:20.154 --> 21:22.907
‐ Were you surprised that
a public service announcement

21:22.907 --> 21:25.993
that you asked your patients
to participate in

21:25.993 --> 21:27.995
ended up
being a bait and switch

21:27.995 --> 21:29.997
to promote OxyContin?

21:29.997 --> 21:33.834
‐ I thought the video
was still very useful.

21:33.834 --> 21:37.588
‐ Well, we've been
interviewing your patients,

21:37.588 --> 21:39.799
and some of them
are clearly addicted to drugs.

21:39.799 --> 21:44.303
As you may know, one of them
died of an overdose.

21:44.303 --> 21:47.348
Another one appears
to be well on his way.

21:49.058 --> 21:51.560
15,000 doctors
were sent a video

21:51.560 --> 21:54.313
with you promoting OxyContin.

21:54.313 --> 21:56.232
And it now appears
that these pills

21:56.232 --> 21:59.235
are a lot more dangerous
than that video claims.

22:01.445 --> 22:03.447
Does that bother you?

22:04.281 --> 22:08.994
‐ What I'm here to do
is to cure pain,

22:08.994 --> 22:13.749
and I shall use everything
in my arsenal to do just that.

22:13.749 --> 22:17.628
Pain has been wildly
undertreated in this country,

22:17.628 --> 22:21.465
and opioids have been
unfairly maligned for years.

22:21.465 --> 22:25.386
OxyContin has worked miracles
for my patients

22:25.386 --> 22:26.804
who have suffered for years

22:26.804 --> 22:30.224
and who are now
getting their lives back.

22:31.892 --> 22:34.228
RANDY: Okay, okay.

22:34.228 --> 22:38.357
So we got a fraudulent
video of people being told

22:38.357 --> 22:42.194
not to discuss the exact drug

22:42.194 --> 22:43.779
that they're in the video
to promote.

22:43.779 --> 22:45.489
‐ Mm‐hmm,
should definitely be enough

22:45.489 --> 22:46.824
for Comey to let us keep going.

22:48.617 --> 22:51.203
‐ Unless he's already
made up his mind.

22:51.203 --> 22:54.582
‐ Would you resign
if he shut us down?

22:56.166 --> 22:58.919
‐ No.
You?

22:58.919 --> 23:00.629
‐ No.

23:00.629 --> 23:02.923
I'd be pissed, though.

23:02.923 --> 23:04.925
You got another ketchup?
[phone ringing]

23:04.925 --> 23:06.760
‐ Yeah.
Hold on quick.

23:09.597 --> 23:11.557
Hello.
This is Randy Ramseyer.

23:11.557 --> 23:13.851
REGINA: Uh, hi,
this is Regina Carter.

23:13.851 --> 23:15.603
You‐‐you left a note
at my apartment.

23:15.603 --> 23:16.979
‐ Yes, that was me.

23:16.979 --> 23:18.731
Uh, I'm an assistant
U. S. attorney,

23:18.731 --> 23:20.900
and I was hoping
that I could interview you

23:20.900 --> 23:24.320
regarding a video that you
were in about five years ago.

23:24.320 --> 23:25.821
REGINA: Okay.

23:25.821 --> 23:28.365
‐ Uh, when‐‐when could we
come see you?

23:28.365 --> 23:29.992
Well, we were hoping
as soon as possible.

23:29.992 --> 23:31.535
We could come by tonight.

23:31.535 --> 23:32.578
REGINA: Tonight?
‐ Yep.

23:32.578 --> 23:34.705
We're just wrapping up
a dinner.

23:34.705 --> 23:35.915
Rick, could you get the check?

23:35.915 --> 23:37.416
And we will, uh‐‐
we'll head on over there.

23:37.416 --> 23:39.668
We'll be over there
in about the next 15, 20.

23:43.505 --> 23:45.049
REGINA: Listen,
what happened with me

23:45.049 --> 23:49.219
was the pill stopped working
'cause my tolerance grew,

23:49.219 --> 23:52.097
and doctors just kept
doubling my dosage.

23:52.097 --> 23:54.892
I was eventually taking
160 milligrams a day.

23:56.685 --> 23:59.605
Started falling asleep at work,

23:59.605 --> 24:01.857
lost my job,

24:01.857 --> 24:04.151
my car,

24:04.151 --> 24:07.112
then my house.

24:07.112 --> 24:08.906
I had to declare bankruptcy.

24:10.074 --> 24:12.201
‐ I am so sorry to hear that.

24:12.201 --> 24:15.955
How did you‐‐how'd you stop
taking the drug?

24:16.956 --> 24:18.874
‐ I weaned myself off.

24:20.584 --> 24:23.295
Hardest thing I ever did.

24:23.295 --> 24:26.423
But I thought, "If I don't
get off this medicine,

24:26.423 --> 24:27.925
I'll end up dead."

24:27.925 --> 24:29.343
‐ And when you realized
you were addicted,

24:29.343 --> 24:30.761
did you go back to Dr. Spanos
to discuss‐‐

24:30.761 --> 24:34.181
‐ Hell no, I never spoke
to that man ever again.

24:35.391 --> 24:37.142
They used us in that video.

24:38.519 --> 24:43.399
I helped a company
make billions selling drugs.

24:46.026 --> 24:48.153
I mean, we were all pawns,

24:48.153 --> 24:50.781
making people think
the drug was non‐addictive.

24:53.283 --> 24:55.452
And I can't help
but feel guilty about that.

24:55.452 --> 24:58.455
‐ Ma'am, you are
not responsible for this.

24:58.455 --> 25:00.332
You are a victim; they lied
to you, they lied to you.

25:00.332 --> 25:04.336
‐ Companies like this, they buy
their way out of trouble.

25:04.336 --> 25:07.381
Black kids selling weed
go to jail for decades.

25:07.381 --> 25:09.925
‐ Well, that's why we're here.

25:13.470 --> 25:14.555
‐ I'm sorry to interrupt.

25:14.555 --> 25:16.515
Is there a restroom
in the lobby?

25:16.515 --> 25:17.516
REGINA: Yeah.

25:17.516 --> 25:20.519
[solemn music]

