29:14.086 --> 29:15.462
Have a good day.

29:37.526 --> 29:40.529
PERSON: Hey!
[struggling]

29:42.531 --> 29:44.283
‐ Hey!
‐ You piece of shit!

29:44.283 --> 29:47.119
BRIDGET: Hey!
‐ [grunts]

29:47.119 --> 29:48.662
BRIDGET: Come on!

29:50.455 --> 29:52.207
Don't you fucking move.

29:54.084 --> 29:55.544
Come on.

30:05.137 --> 30:07.139
Have you ever heard
of the crack epidemic?

30:09.641 --> 30:11.560
It was big
in poor neighborhoods

30:11.560 --> 30:13.645
in the 1980s.

30:13.645 --> 30:15.897
Huge portions
of the Black population

30:15.897 --> 30:17.482
were hooked on crack.

30:18.483 --> 30:21.236
I grew up in D. C.
during this time,

30:21.236 --> 30:23.780
and there was this convenience
store across the street

30:23.780 --> 30:25.282
from my grandma's apartment.

30:25.282 --> 30:28.827
And the parking lot
was a warzone.

30:28.827 --> 30:33.040
People selling drugs,
killing each other.

30:35.042 --> 30:38.128
My grandma got mugged
three times.

30:40.213 --> 30:43.216
This was how I grew up, Lucas.

30:44.176 --> 30:46.345
Watching my friends die
from drugs.

30:49.264 --> 30:52.142
If you continue on this path,

30:52.142 --> 30:54.895
you're going to end up
just like them.

30:57.522 --> 30:59.858
‐ Is your grandma okay now?

31:01.526 --> 31:02.903
‐ She's fine.

31:04.488 --> 31:06.490
Thanks for asking.

31:07.949 --> 31:09.576
‐ I didn't want her money.
I was...

31:10.786 --> 31:13.455
I was trying to steal
her prescription.

31:13.455 --> 31:15.332
‐ How do you know she had one?

31:16.875 --> 31:19.127
LUCAS: She came out
of the pain clinic.

31:20.045 --> 31:22.255
That's where everyone gets
their Oxy prescriptions.

31:23.715 --> 31:26.051
BRIDGET: And what would you
do with it?

31:26.051 --> 31:29.971
‐ There's a girl in my class,
eighth grade.

31:29.971 --> 31:34.059
And she's got this older
brother that makes fake IDs,

31:34.059 --> 31:37.270
so we use it to get
the prescription filled.

31:38.397 --> 31:40.440
Take half
and sell the other half.

31:40.440 --> 31:45.278
‐ How many kids in your school
are on OxyContin?

31:45.278 --> 31:46.988
‐ I don't know.

31:49.157 --> 31:51.243
Maybe half.

31:51.243 --> 31:56.248
♪ ♪

31:56.248 --> 31:58.125
‐ Now how about here?
Any pain?

31:58.125 --> 31:59.709
‐ Nope.

31:59.709 --> 32:01.545
‐ If I lift higher,
does that hurt?

32:01.545 --> 32:03.046
‐ [chuckles]
Don't feel a thing.

32:03.046 --> 32:06.591
‐ And you‐‐and you feel like
you have full range of motion?

32:06.591 --> 32:10.220
‐ Yeah.
Just like before.

32:10.220 --> 32:12.431
‐ You think the drug
lasted 12 hours?

32:12.431 --> 32:15.183
‐ Well, I didn't time it.
‐ How about sleep?

32:15.183 --> 32:17.144
Any problems sleeping
through the night?

32:17.144 --> 32:19.604
‐ No, it worked like a charm.

32:19.604 --> 32:21.440
I actually went bowling
last week.

32:24.025 --> 32:26.445
I didn't think I'd ever get
to go bowling again.

32:27.612 --> 32:30.490
I appreciate it, Doc,

32:32.325 --> 32:33.618
‐ Sure about this, Doc?

32:33.618 --> 32:34.995
I'll take you to any steakhouse
in the state.

32:34.995 --> 32:37.080
‐ Uh‐uh, I'm sure as can be.

32:37.080 --> 32:38.623
Mmm, look at that pie.

32:38.623 --> 32:40.417
You can't beat the chicken
here at Nancy's.

32:40.417 --> 32:41.793
BO: What can I get you, Doc?
‐ Hey, Bo.

32:41.793 --> 32:43.336
You know what I like.

32:43.336 --> 32:45.213
BO: For you?
‐ Uh, I'll have the same.

32:46.465 --> 32:48.258
SAMUEL:
You and your dad close?

32:48.258 --> 32:52.512
‐ Um, not really.

32:52.512 --> 32:55.682
He's a writer and a professor.

32:55.682 --> 32:58.143
Brother writes short stories,
so they're close.

32:58.143 --> 33:00.562
Mom's a poet.
‐ Really?

33:00.562 --> 33:01.938
BILLY: Yeah.

33:01.938 --> 33:05.609
I'm sort of the, uh,
Roger Clinton of the family.

33:05.609 --> 33:07.736
‐ Huh.

33:07.736 --> 33:10.989
Well...

33:10.989 --> 33:12.991
I'm sure they're
very proud of you.

33:12.991 --> 33:14.493
‐ Yeah.

33:17.579 --> 33:20.999
So, um, you ever think
about dating again, or...

33:20.999 --> 33:23.335
‐ Nah.
No interest.

33:23.335 --> 33:26.755
‐ Well, you should come to our
weekend seminar in Scottsdale.

33:26.755 --> 33:28.173
‐ Mm.

33:28.173 --> 33:31.259
‐ They're a ton of fun,
and it's all expenses paid,

33:31.259 --> 33:33.553
and a ton of
interesting women there.

33:33.553 --> 33:34.638
‐ Mm‐hmm.

33:34.638 --> 33:37.641
‐ Doctors, nurses,
pain specialists.

33:37.641 --> 33:39.643
Russell Portenoy
is gonna speak.

33:41.645 --> 33:44.898
‐ He is?
‐ Yeah, he's the main speaker.

33:46.191 --> 33:49.486
‐ You know, when Shelly
was in the hospital,

33:49.486 --> 33:52.656
I read some of his articles,
and, uh,

33:52.656 --> 33:54.032
they really helped.

33:54.032 --> 33:55.200
Gotta say.

33:56.785 --> 33:59.746
Do me a favor
if you think of it.

33:59.746 --> 34:04.709
Uh, mention to him
that, uh, I'm really grateful.

34:04.709 --> 34:06.253
So thank you.

34:07.629 --> 34:09.464
‐ Come to the seminar
in Scottsdale

34:09.464 --> 34:11.550
and tell him yourself.

34:11.550 --> 34:14.553
[tense music]

34:14.553 --> 34:21.560
♪ ♪

34:27.190 --> 34:28.942
‐ Hey, Mom?

34:28.942 --> 34:30.110
DIANE: Yes, dear?

34:35.365 --> 34:37.701
‐ I think there's something
we should talk about.

34:39.536 --> 34:40.745
DIANE: Okay.

34:43.498 --> 34:44.749
‐ Uh...

34:47.752 --> 34:50.130
This may be hard
for you to hear, but...

34:50.130 --> 34:51.131
[clears throat]

34:54.009 --> 34:56.678
I like girls.

34:59.055 --> 35:00.599
I always have.

35:03.935 --> 35:05.937
Not just as friends.

35:12.861 --> 35:16.072
And I know‐‐I know Dad
is gonna be real upset,

35:16.072 --> 35:19.492
but maybe you could talk to him

35:19.492 --> 35:23.038
and tell him that nothing's
gonna be different.

35:23.038 --> 35:27.292
I'm‐‐I'm still the same person.

35:29.878 --> 35:31.171
I promise I am.

35:31.171 --> 35:32.672
I just...

35:39.429 --> 35:41.348
I can't live like this anymore.

35:41.348 --> 35:43.391
I just wanna be myself.

35:47.687 --> 35:49.189
‐ I'm sorry, dear.

35:49.189 --> 35:52.108
Did you say something to me?

35:59.240 --> 36:00.492
‐ No.

36:00.492 --> 36:07.499
♪ ♪

36:50.166 --> 36:53.878
[Elvis Presley's
"Blue Christmas" playing]

36:53.878 --> 36:55.797
GRACE: How much those run you?

36:57.549 --> 36:59.551
‐ I'm ready.

36:59.551 --> 37:00.760
‐ For what?

37:02.637 --> 37:03.763
‐ I want to do it.

37:03.763 --> 37:05.473
I want to move
to Eureka Springs.

37:05.473 --> 37:07.892
ELVIS: ♪ Blue, blue,
blue Christmas ♪

37:07.892 --> 37:09.269
‐ Are you kidding me?

37:10.895 --> 37:13.690
‐ I've been feeling
a lot better this past week.

37:15.483 --> 37:19.821
And I realized you were right.

37:19.821 --> 37:21.072
Coal's a job.

37:21.072 --> 37:23.074
It's‐‐it's not a life.

37:27.245 --> 37:28.913
I want my life with you.

37:31.666 --> 37:34.502
ELVIS: ♪ You'll be doing
all right... ♪

37:34.502 --> 37:38.590
‐ Your face is so pretty, Bets.

37:38.590 --> 37:41.050
It should never be
covered in soot.

37:42.886 --> 37:49.893
ELVIS: ♪ But I'll have a blue,
blue, blue, blue Christmas ♪

37:49.893 --> 37:53.938
♪ ♪

37:57.942 --> 38:02.197
SINGER:
♪ She rides to the sun too ♪

38:02.197 --> 38:06.284
♪ Lights fade
as she casts her spell ♪

38:06.284 --> 38:08.036
♪ ♪

38:08.036 --> 38:10.705
RICK: Hey, Bridget.
We heard this was your spot.

38:10.705 --> 38:12.248
‐ Oh, what the fuck?

38:12.248 --> 38:14.626
‐ Hey, Bridget.
Great to see you again.

38:14.626 --> 38:16.795
How's your divorce coming?

38:16.795 --> 38:19.464
‐ It's finalized.
Want a drink?

38:19.464 --> 38:21.925
‐ Uh, neither of us drink.

38:21.925 --> 38:24.260
‐ Not surprised.

38:24.260 --> 38:25.512
RICK: You don't have
to be like this.

38:25.512 --> 38:27.263
We're on the same side.

38:27.263 --> 38:29.224
‐ [scoffs]

38:29.224 --> 38:31.684
I'm helping you.

38:31.684 --> 38:34.062
I'm saving you
from wasting your time.

38:34.062 --> 38:38.274
The FDA, Justice, the doctors,
they all want their drugs.

38:38.274 --> 38:40.568
And big pharma will
spend everything they can

38:40.568 --> 38:43.029
to make sure
that they get them.

38:43.029 --> 38:45.365
And this is just gonna
keep going and going

38:45.365 --> 38:49.077
till we're all just one big
pill‐popping zombie nation.

38:49.077 --> 38:52.330
‐ Have you seen Purdue's
I Got My Life Back video?

38:53.414 --> 38:55.250
‐ Sure.
‐ It's a fraud.

38:55.250 --> 38:57.293
They were told it was a PSA
when they shot it.

38:58.586 --> 39:00.922
And several of those
participants became addicted.

39:00.922 --> 39:04.843
‐ Few of them are dead
or close to it.

39:06.761 --> 39:09.097
‐ [sighs]

39:14.143 --> 39:15.937
You know who'd be
interested in that?

39:18.064 --> 39:20.400
Sarah Miller and Judy Cohen.

39:20.400 --> 39:21.818
‐ Sarah Miller, Judy Cohen.

39:21.818 --> 39:25.613
‐ At the DOJ's office
of consumer litigation.

39:25.613 --> 39:28.116
‐ Well, I thought
they were all conspirators

39:28.116 --> 39:30.869
in the upcoming
zombie apocalypse.

39:30.869 --> 39:32.453
‐ Not everybody.

39:35.999 --> 39:37.584
Now, that was my tip
for the day, boys,

39:37.584 --> 39:39.043
so if you can both
kindly fuck off,

39:39.043 --> 39:40.712
I'd certainly
be better off for it.

39:42.672 --> 39:44.132
‐ Thank you, Bridget.

39:47.802 --> 39:50.096
‐ I'm sorry about your divorce.

39:54.559 --> 39:56.352
PERSON:
I'm at a loss for words.

39:56.352 --> 40:00.356
It‐‐it‐‐it‐‐it almost makes me
want to tear up a little bit,

40:00.356 --> 40:03.443
but I‐‐it‐‐it's just changed
my life for the better.

40:03.443 --> 40:06.070
‐ I'm coming home
with energy to spare.

40:06.070 --> 40:08.489
Just to have the evening
to do things with

40:08.489 --> 40:09.782
was unheard of.

40:09.782 --> 40:11.659
[phone ringing]

40:11.659 --> 40:13.995
‐ We've been having problems
with Purdue from the get‐go.

40:13.995 --> 40:17.248
‐ Like the label?
‐ Like the label.

40:17.248 --> 40:18.708
‐ So when Curtis Wright
approved

40:18.708 --> 40:21.669
the original FDA label,
was there internal pushback?

40:21.669 --> 40:23.129
SARAH: Oh, yeah.

40:23.129 --> 40:24.547
Diane Schnitzler
emailed him that

40:24.547 --> 40:26.382
Purdue's "less addictive"
claims sounded like bullshit.

40:26.382 --> 40:28.176
RICK:
What was Mr. Wright's response?

40:28.176 --> 40:31.971
‐ He said, "Actually, Diane,
this is literally true."

40:31.971 --> 40:36.476
‐ So Curtis Wright is
the FDA medical review officer

40:36.476 --> 40:39.771
who approves an unprecedented
label for Purdue.

40:39.771 --> 40:42.732
And then he goes
and he works for Purdue.

40:42.732 --> 40:46.361
So do you think there's
quid pro quo with Purdue

40:46.361 --> 40:48.029
to grant such generous wording?

40:48.029 --> 40:49.364
‐ Yeah, well, I get that

40:49.364 --> 40:52.742
it has the appearance
of corruption,

40:52.742 --> 40:54.911
but it's possible there wasn't.

40:54.911 --> 41:00.750
What Curtis Wright did
is the way the industry works.

41:00.750 --> 41:02.168
It's a revolving door

41:02.168 --> 41:04.295
where as soon as people
leave the government,

41:04.295 --> 41:07.548
they go and work for the exact
people they were regulating

41:07.548 --> 41:11.469
for five times the money,
and it's all legal.

41:11.469 --> 41:12.470
‐ What appears to be corruption

41:12.470 --> 41:14.430
is simply how the system works.

41:14.430 --> 41:18.518
‐ Here's an ad, says patient
only needs two pills a day,

41:18.518 --> 41:20.812
but the drug often
didn't last 12 hours.

41:20.812 --> 41:21.938
So how does an ad like this

41:21.938 --> 41:23.898
get through the FDA
approval process?

41:23.898 --> 41:25.483
‐ You'll have to ask
Ronald Reagan.

41:25.483 --> 41:27.819
‐ Does he work
for Purdue now too?

41:27.819 --> 41:30.029
‐ No, but when
he gutted the FDA,

41:30.029 --> 41:31.364
they went from policing
big pharma

41:31.364 --> 41:33.074
to being at their mercy.

41:33.074 --> 41:37.495
39 employees are responsible
for 35,000 promotional items.

41:37.495 --> 41:39.622
‐ How do they grant
proper oversight?

41:39.622 --> 41:41.332
‐ Just give me five minutes.

41:43.376 --> 41:47.005
It works as an honor system.

41:47.005 --> 41:49.507
Drug companies
are supposed to be honest.

41:49.507 --> 41:51.801
‐ [laughs]
‐ I know.

41:51.801 --> 41:54.220
‐ So if a company was being
criminally dishonest

41:54.220 --> 41:56.055
in its promotional marketing,

41:56.055 --> 41:57.473
what would you charge them with

41:57.473 --> 42:00.226
if‐‐if fraud
was too high a bar?

42:00.226 --> 42:01.561
JUDY: Sarah?

42:01.561 --> 42:02.979
‐ Can you all give us a moment?

42:14.574 --> 42:17.869
If it were me, I'd charge them
with criminal misbranding.

42:17.869 --> 42:19.245
‐ Never heard of that before.

42:19.245 --> 42:20.705
SARAH: Most people haven't.

42:20.705 --> 42:22.832
It's perfect for this because
you don't have to prove

42:22.832 --> 42:24.542
the misbranding
caused the overdoses

42:24.542 --> 42:26.169
or pin it on an individual,

42:26.169 --> 42:29.380
just that the company
misbranded the drug.

42:29.380 --> 42:32.383
[dramatic music]

42:32.383 --> 42:34.135
♪ ♪

42:34.135 --> 42:35.470
‐ Thank you.

42:35.470 --> 42:37.305
‐ You're welcome.

42:37.305 --> 42:38.890
‐ I want more hot water.

42:38.890 --> 42:41.434
‐ More hot water?
You're already boiling.

42:41.434 --> 42:43.853
I think that's enough.
All right, sweetheart?

42:43.853 --> 42:45.354
You stick your tongue out
at me?

42:45.354 --> 42:47.565
Let me take that.
Oh, I got it.

42:49.192 --> 42:51.277
I got your tongue.
It's pretty good.

42:51.277 --> 42:52.528
[phone ringing]

42:52.528 --> 42:54.447
Okay.
Shh, shh, shh.

42:54.447 --> 42:55.448
What do you got?

42:55.448 --> 42:56.866
PERSON: Nothing good.

42:56.866 --> 42:58.326
Main Justice
doesn't like the pharma case.

42:58.326 --> 42:59.911
‐ But wait‐‐wait‐‐
wait a minute, wait a minute.

42:59.911 --> 43:01.204
Do you know why?

43:01.204 --> 43:02.914
Seems pretty early
to pull the plug on me.

43:02.914 --> 43:04.332
PERSON: I don't have details.

43:04.332 --> 43:06.918
Just that Comey
doesn't like the case.

43:06.918 --> 43:09.545
‐ All right, got it.
Thanks.

43:09.545 --> 43:11.422
LEE: What's wrong?

43:11.422 --> 43:14.133
‐ DAG wants to shut
my pharma case down.

43:14.133 --> 43:15.843
‐ Isn't that a little fast?

43:19.263 --> 43:20.890
‐ I always knew
there was a chance

43:20.890 --> 43:23.976
we might get shut down
by Main Justice.

43:23.976 --> 43:26.687
It's pretty crappy
if you ask me.

43:26.687 --> 43:29.065
‐ I wouldn't say "crappy"
when we go to Comey.

43:29.065 --> 43:31.275
He doesn't like
that kind of language.

43:31.275 --> 43:33.277
‐ No, that's Ashcroft.

43:33.277 --> 43:36.239
I heard he dressed Comey down
one time for saying "turd."

43:38.908 --> 43:40.701
Comey tells us the case is off,
I'm gonna say,

43:40.701 --> 43:42.787
"Well, that's one big
turd burger, sir."

43:42.787 --> 43:44.372
‐ [laughs]

43:44.372 --> 43:47.250
‐ So, uh, listen,
day after we get back,

43:47.250 --> 43:48.584
I gotta have surgery.

43:48.584 --> 43:50.711
I'm gonna be out for a week.

43:50.711 --> 43:51.754
‐ You okay?

43:53.589 --> 43:55.424
‐ I have prostate cancer.

43:56.467 --> 43:59.262
It took 'em a minute
to find it, but it's fine.

43:59.262 --> 44:01.055
They don't think it spread.

44:01.055 --> 44:03.057
Just, uh‐‐just need a week.

44:06.435 --> 44:09.021
‐ I'm so sorry, Randy.

44:09.021 --> 44:13.734
Just take two weeks off,
or three, as long as you need.

44:13.734 --> 44:16.028
‐ No, I just need a week.

44:18.614 --> 44:20.199
‐ Is it okay if I pray for you?

44:23.619 --> 44:26.122
‐ Right now?
‐ I could.

44:26.122 --> 44:31.043
‐ Oh, no.
No, it's all right.

44:31.043 --> 44:34.088
It's not really my thing.

44:34.088 --> 44:35.923
Thank you, though.

44:35.923 --> 44:38.634
I just want to see
if I can find some napkins.

44:44.056 --> 44:47.059
‐ [praying indistinctly]

44:50.062 --> 44:51.939
‐ Okay, so just
let me handle this.

44:51.939 --> 44:55.526
Even if Comey says we're dead,
it doesn't mean we're dead.

44:55.526 --> 44:56.736
‐ Then what does it mean?

44:56.736 --> 44:58.112
‐ It means we're dead.

45:00.489 --> 45:03.784
JAMES: Getting some complaints
about your investigation.

45:03.784 --> 45:05.286
That it's out of control.

45:05.286 --> 45:08.122
[dramatic music]

45:08.122 --> 45:10.917
‐ Well, that's just
not true, sir.

45:10.917 --> 45:13.753
We‐‐we've been doing
this whole thing by the book.

45:13.753 --> 45:16.047
These guys are behaving
like pros.

45:16.047 --> 45:18.466
And this is a very serious
issue that warrants

45:18.466 --> 45:20.801
all the attention
we've been giving it.

45:20.801 --> 45:22.470
‐ Serious?

45:22.470 --> 45:25.348
Well, how serious
does chicken get?

45:25.348 --> 45:27.391
‐ Chicken?
‐ Chicken, sir?

45:27.391 --> 45:29.936
‐ Yes, chicken.

45:29.936 --> 45:33.814
‐ What do you‐‐what
do you mean by chicken?

45:33.814 --> 45:35.358
RANDY: Do you mean, like,

45:35.358 --> 45:37.985
chicken the food
or chicken you're scared?

45:37.985 --> 45:40.655
Like you‐‐you're a chicken?

45:40.655 --> 45:42.240
‐ Chicken, the food.

45:45.076 --> 45:48.120
Why are you investigating
the chicken guy?

45:48.120 --> 45:49.372
‐ Colonel Sanders?

45:49.372 --> 45:51.582
‐ No, Frank Perdue.

45:53.042 --> 45:55.962
‐ Oh, no, sir.
No, no, no, no.

45:55.962 --> 45:59.006
Uh, we are not investigating
Perdue Farms.

45:59.006 --> 46:01.717
We are investigating
Purdue Pharma.

46:01.717 --> 46:03.511
It's‐‐it's spelled
differently, I think.

46:03.511 --> 46:06.973
Yeah, it's spelled with a
"U" instead of an "E."

46:06.973 --> 46:08.516
Yeah, Purdue Pharma.

46:08.516 --> 46:11.519
No, it's the company
that manufactures OxyContin.

46:11.519 --> 46:15.022
It's not the‐‐the, um‐‐
it's not the chicken people.

46:17.650 --> 46:20.569
‐ Well, my staff must have
been misinformed.

46:20.569 --> 46:22.113
‐ Well, perhaps whoever's
complaining about us

46:22.113 --> 46:24.240
is trying to get you
off our track, sir.

46:24.240 --> 46:26.701
And for good reason.
It's early days.

46:26.701 --> 46:28.327
We already have
substantial leads.

46:28.327 --> 46:31.330
Manipulative advertising,
false claims about addiction,

46:31.330 --> 46:34.000
overdoses are skyrocketing
while Purdue continues to lie

46:34.000 --> 46:35.543
about the drug's safety
to doctors,

46:35.543 --> 46:38.462
to patients, and the FDA.

46:38.462 --> 46:40.673
We have a major case here.

46:40.673 --> 46:45.261
♪ ♪

46:45.261 --> 46:47.013
‐ Well, then go
make your case.

46:52.268 --> 46:53.269
[upbeat funky music]

46:53.269 --> 46:54.937
SINGER: ♪ Yeah ♪

46:54.937 --> 46:56.480
♪ Can you feel it, baby? ♪

46:56.480 --> 46:58.858
SINGERS: ♪ Ooh ♪

46:58.858 --> 47:00.443
SINGER: ♪ I can too ♪

47:00.443 --> 47:02.278
SINGERS: ♪ Ooh ♪

47:02.278 --> 47:04.322
♪ ♪

47:04.322 --> 47:05.781
♪ Ooh ♪

47:05.781 --> 47:08.451
♪ ♪

47:08.451 --> 47:09.910
♪ Ooh ♪

47:09.910 --> 47:12.288
SINGER: ♪ I'm gonna swing,
come on, swing ♪

47:12.288 --> 47:14.081
SINGERS: ♪ Ooh ♪

47:14.081 --> 47:16.250
SINGER: ♪ Come on, swing,
c‐come on, swing ♪

47:16.250 --> 47:17.835
STAFF: Hey, can I offer you

47:17.835 --> 47:20.171
a complementary OxyContin
bucket hat?

47:20.171 --> 47:21.213
‐ Uh, no.

47:21.213 --> 47:22.214
‐ Maybe one of
our compact discs?

47:22.214 --> 47:23.466
‐ No, thanks.
‐ All right.

47:23.466 --> 47:25.509
Hey, well, enjoy your day.
‐ Okay, thanks.

47:25.509 --> 47:27.053
BILLY: Dr. Finnix, so glad
you could make it.

47:27.053 --> 47:28.804
SAMUEL: Thanks.
‐ Hell of a spread, right?

47:28.804 --> 47:30.348
‐ Oh, you bet.

47:30.348 --> 47:31.349
‐ I wasn't lying to you.

47:31.349 --> 47:32.725
‐ No, you weren't.

47:32.725 --> 47:35.936
‐ Um, I wanted to introduce you
to Dr. Russell Portenoy.

47:35.936 --> 47:37.313
‐ Pleasure to meet you.
‐ Oh, no.

47:37.313 --> 47:38.689
The honor's all mine.
Believe me.

47:38.689 --> 47:40.066
‐ You're very kind.

47:40.066 --> 47:42.985
‐ Uh...

47:42.985 --> 47:44.862
I feel a little silly,
to be honest with you,

47:44.862 --> 47:48.532
but I actually brought
your book down

47:48.532 --> 47:51.202
and I wonder
if you'd sign it for me

47:51.202 --> 47:52.870
over the weekend
if you have a chance.

47:52.870 --> 47:54.789
‐ Are you kidding?
It'd be my honor.

47:54.789 --> 47:56.749
‐ All right, great.
‐ Great.

47:56.749 --> 48:00.002
Well, look, don't let us get
between you and the food.

48:00.002 --> 48:01.754
Don't miss out on that lobster.
SAMUEL: All right, Billy.

48:01.754 --> 48:03.005
‐ And, uh,
we'll see you shortly.

48:03.005 --> 48:04.131
We're just over here.
SAMUEL: All right.

48:04.131 --> 48:05.758
‐ All right, Doc.

48:05.758 --> 48:07.510
‐ We're honored
that you'd take a break

48:07.510 --> 48:10.221
from your busy schedules
to spend the weekend with us,

48:10.221 --> 48:13.224
and‐‐as well as‐‐

48:13.224 --> 48:16.268
the country's leading
independent pain organizations.

48:16.268 --> 48:20.398
We have representatives from
the American Pain Foundation,

48:20.398 --> 48:23.359
the National Foundation
for the Treatment of Pain,

48:23.359 --> 48:25.444
American Chronic
Pain Association,

48:25.444 --> 48:26.862
the American Pain Society,

48:26.862 --> 48:30.157
and the American Academy
of Pain Medicine.

48:30.157 --> 48:33.452
[applause]

48:33.452 --> 48:36.372
But to start us off,
we wanna begin

48:36.372 --> 48:39.750
with the foremost
pain specialist in the country.

48:39.750 --> 48:43.129
He is co‐chief of the Pain
and Palliative care Service

48:43.129 --> 48:46.966
at Sloan‐Kettering,
Dr. Russell Portenoy.

48:46.966 --> 48:49.176
[applause]

48:49.176 --> 48:52.179
[tense dramatic music]

48:52.179 --> 48:54.515
‐ This is truly
a special moment

48:54.515 --> 48:56.475
in the history of pain care.

48:56.475 --> 49:00.771
Hospitals, doctors,
think tanks, and even the FDA

49:00.771 --> 49:04.358
are rethinking the very nature
of pain treatment.

49:04.358 --> 49:08.446
And what we've learned is
that opioids, certain kinds,

49:08.446 --> 49:12.116
are not nearly as addictive
as they have been perceived.

49:12.116 --> 49:13.868
Narcotics can be abused

49:13.868 --> 49:17.121
and are not appropriate
in all instances.

49:17.121 --> 49:20.124
But when properly
prescribed by doctors,

49:20.124 --> 49:23.961
they almost never lead
to addiction.

49:23.961 --> 49:26.964
[applause]

49:28.466 --> 49:30.551
‐ In most immediate‐release
opioids,

49:30.551 --> 49:35.306
blood plasma levels spike
between euphoria and pain.

49:35.306 --> 49:37.308
But OxyContin's
time‐release system

49:37.308 --> 49:38.517
causes blood plasma levels

49:38.517 --> 49:40.478
to have
fewer peaks and valleys,

49:40.478 --> 49:42.521
creating a plateau effect,

49:42.521 --> 49:46.984
which results in less euphoria
and less potential for abuse.

49:46.984 --> 49:51.489
‐ And did‐‐did doctors attend
these weekend seminars?

49:51.489 --> 49:53.657
‐ Yes, many of them did.

49:53.657 --> 49:55.201
BILLY:
This is Dr. Samuel Finnix.

49:55.201 --> 49:57.119
Runs a patient care practice
in Appalachia.

49:57.119 --> 50:00.289
And, Drea here, we stole
from Johnson and Johnson

50:00.289 --> 50:02.500
and she, uh,
she runs the South.

50:02.500 --> 50:04.126
Covers multiple
Southern territories for us.

50:04.126 --> 50:05.753
‐ It's an honor to meet you.

50:05.753 --> 50:07.129
‐ Nice to meet you.

50:07.129 --> 50:08.547
‐ I'm from a small town
in Alabama,

50:08.547 --> 50:10.966
so I know how important
the local doctor is.

50:10.966 --> 50:12.510
SAMUEL: Yeah.

50:12.510 --> 50:15.054
‐ Have you been prescribing
OxyContin to your miners?

50:15.054 --> 50:16.680
‐ To a few, yeah.

50:16.680 --> 50:18.224
Yeah, it's been‐‐
it's been effective.

50:18.224 --> 50:20.726
‐ And what occurred
at these events?

50:22.228 --> 50:25.898
‐ Doctors were often co‐opted
by Purdue Pharma.

50:25.898 --> 50:27.691
‐ You should do a talk
with Dr. Finnix.

50:27.691 --> 50:30.027
I bet people would love
to hear about his patients.

50:30.027 --> 50:32.571
BILLY: Great idea.
Yeah, well, what do you think?

50:32.571 --> 50:33.864
‐ No, I‐I can't really

50:33.864 --> 50:35.991
get up and speak
in front of people.

50:35.991 --> 50:38.118
DREA: Oh, please.
You're far more impressive.

50:38.118 --> 50:39.745
You're on the front lines.

50:39.745 --> 50:41.205
Just think how incredible
it would be

50:41.205 --> 50:42.706
if the story of a coal town

50:42.706 --> 50:46.752
could help change lives
all over the country.

50:46.752 --> 50:48.921
‐ Absolutely.
And I mean, it'd be easy.

50:48.921 --> 50:50.422
You know, I'd be asking you
the questions

50:50.422 --> 50:52.007
so you don't have
to embellish anything.

50:52.007 --> 50:54.468
Just, uh, tell people
what you're seeing.

50:54.468 --> 50:55.678
‐ It'd be wonderful
for these city boys

50:55.678 --> 50:58.264
to see how us country folks
get things done.

50:58.264 --> 51:02.059
‐ Yeah.
Well, uh, sure.

51:02.059 --> 51:03.602
Okay, I guess.

51:03.602 --> 51:05.187
You're gonna ask me
the questions?

51:05.187 --> 51:07.231
‐ Absolutely.
I'll be right with you.

51:07.231 --> 51:10.985
‐ All right, well.
See how that goes.

51:10.985 --> 51:14.530
‐ So, uh, Dr. Samuel Finnix,
tell us, what kind of ailments

51:14.530 --> 51:16.615
do your patients
typically have?

51:16.615 --> 51:19.868
‐ Many of my patients
are miners,

51:19.868 --> 51:23.330
so I see back injuries,
shoulder lacerations,

51:23.330 --> 51:25.666
broken hands, things like that.

51:25.666 --> 51:27.876
‐ And you would say,
in your experience,

51:27.876 --> 51:32.089
pain is part of everyday life
in the mines?

51:32.089 --> 51:34.717
‐ Yes, it is.
Yes.

51:39.597 --> 51:43.892
‐ I‐I have, um, uh,
firsthand experience of pain.

51:43.892 --> 51:48.355
My father was diagnosed
with a rare form of cancer.

51:48.355 --> 51:49.565
‐ Oh, I'm sorry.

51:49.565 --> 51:50.983
BILLY: Thank you.
Which he survived,

51:50.983 --> 51:53.569
but watching him
suffer through that

51:53.569 --> 51:56.363
was one of the‐‐the hardest
things that I've been through.

51:56.363 --> 51:58.866
You also have
firsthand experience

51:58.866 --> 52:00.701
with that kind of pain, right?

52:00.701 --> 52:02.453
‐ I do, yeah.

52:02.453 --> 52:05.539
Uh, my wife had cancer, um,

52:05.539 --> 52:11.086
and, uh, well, she passed away;
she didn't make it.

52:11.086 --> 52:12.713
‐ I'm so sorry.

52:12.713 --> 52:14.298
Purdue's drug, MS Contin,

52:14.298 --> 52:18.844
was very helpful to her
in her final days, wasn't it?

52:18.844 --> 52:21.347
‐ It was.
It was‐‐it was helpful.

52:21.347 --> 52:24.600
That's why I wanted
to try OxyContin

52:24.600 --> 52:28.228
on my patients because, uh,
I don't want them to suffer.

52:28.228 --> 52:29.647
If there's a drug out there

52:29.647 --> 52:32.733
that can help them,
well, then I‐I want to try.

52:32.733 --> 52:36.612
‐ And the patients are wanting
to try it, too, right?

52:36.612 --> 52:38.781
‐ Heck yeah, they are.

52:38.781 --> 52:41.784
[applause]

52:50.709 --> 52:53.587
I know most people don't,
you know,

52:53.587 --> 52:56.256
they don't think about us
up there in the mountains.

52:56.256 --> 53:03.222
Uh, but these people,

53:03.222 --> 53:05.683
you know,

53:05.683 --> 53:07.893
when this country needed
to build airplanes,

53:07.893 --> 53:10.229
uh, during World War II
overnight,

53:10.229 --> 53:12.815
where‐‐where do you think
that steel came from?

53:12.815 --> 53:16.318
The bridges we drive across,
the high rises you live in,

53:16.318 --> 53:19.530
stadiums
where we all watch football,

53:19.530 --> 53:21.865
that's all‐‐that's steel.

53:21.865 --> 53:23.784
And steel comes from coal.

53:25.953 --> 53:27.579
Um, I'm probably
talking too much.

53:27.579 --> 53:28.580
Am I talking too much?

53:28.580 --> 53:30.082
‐ No, please, please.

53:30.082 --> 53:34.211
‐ And who do you think digs
that coal out of the‐‐

53:34.211 --> 53:36.380
out of the mountains
in the hollows?

53:36.380 --> 53:38.382
My patients do.

53:38.382 --> 53:40.467
It's dangerous work, and...

53:40.467 --> 53:42.720
they risk their lives every day

53:42.720 --> 53:45.180
to keeps the lights on
in places like this.

53:45.180 --> 53:47.599
To keep the lights on
in the big cities.

53:47.599 --> 53:50.936
Keep the lights on
in your fine homes.

53:50.936 --> 53:52.938
And, uh, they carry the burden

53:52.938 --> 53:55.315
of building this nation
on their backs,

53:55.315 --> 53:57.276
and they deserve to do it
without pain.

53:57.276 --> 54:03.782
So if this drug can help
these good folks

54:03.782 --> 54:06.785
have a better life
and feed their families,

54:06.785 --> 54:11.248
well, then Purdue Pharma
is doing these people,

54:11.248 --> 54:15.586
my people, a great service,
so...

54:15.586 --> 54:18.338
God bless them for it.

54:18.338 --> 54:21.884
[cheers and applause]

54:33.103 --> 54:34.563
‐ Were you nervous?
‐ Yeah.

54:34.563 --> 54:35.981
‐ Oh, well,
you didn't look nervous.

54:35.981 --> 54:37.107
You were incredible.
‐ Would you excuse me?

54:37.107 --> 54:38.442
‐ You were
absolutely incredible.

54:38.442 --> 54:39.902
I've been to hundreds
of these, and seriously,

54:39.902 --> 54:41.570
I've never been so moved.

54:41.570 --> 54:42.988
‐ Oh, thank you.
‐ Really appreciate it.

54:42.988 --> 54:44.406
‐ Hey, Daniel.
Do you mind if I steal

54:44.406 --> 54:46.408
the star of the weekend
for just a few minutes?

54:46.408 --> 54:48.076
‐ Of course not‐‐thank you.
Nice talking to you.

54:48.076 --> 54:49.495
‐ Nice talking to you.

54:49.495 --> 54:53.415
‐ I have to tell you,
you spoke for the people

54:53.415 --> 54:57.711
that don't often
get a voice in this country.

54:57.711 --> 55:01.173
‐ Well, look, thanks
for getting me up there.

55:01.173 --> 55:02.633
‐ Oh, it was beautiful.

55:02.633 --> 55:04.760
You know, Purdue
has a speaker's bureau.

55:04.760 --> 55:07.763
They'd be lucky to have you.
Is this okay?

55:07.763 --> 55:10.432
SAMUEL: Yeah.
What's that?

55:10.432 --> 55:11.934
‐ Oh, we pay speakers

55:11.934 --> 55:14.061
to go to events
like this around the country.

55:14.061 --> 55:17.648
They get $500 to $3,000
for a speech.

55:17.648 --> 55:18.982
‐ Those speakers get paid?

55:18.982 --> 55:21.026
‐ Oh, yeah.
It's not a secret.

55:21.026 --> 55:22.861
You should think about it.

55:22.861 --> 55:25.781
‐ You were great up there.

55:25.781 --> 55:27.658
That guy's amazing.

55:27.658 --> 55:29.701
‐ Mm.
Yeah.

55:29.701 --> 55:33.247
He's, uh‐‐he's really special.

55:33.247 --> 55:36.500
‐ And I'm sorry about your dad.

55:36.500 --> 55:37.918
Is he okay now?

55:39.753 --> 55:41.839
‐ Yeah, I, uh...

55:43.841 --> 55:45.384
I made that up.

55:46.343 --> 55:50.472
My, uh‐‐my dad
never had cancer.

55:50.472 --> 55:52.057
[piano music playing]

55:52.057 --> 55:53.809
‐ [laughs]

55:53.809 --> 55:54.893
Wow.

55:54.893 --> 55:56.728
This is the first time

55:56.728 --> 55:58.814
that I've ever wanted
to fuck you.

55:58.814 --> 56:01.650
[both laughing]

56:03.694 --> 56:05.821
Huh.

56:05.821 --> 56:08.866
‐ You, uh‐‐you want to do
something about that?

56:08.866 --> 56:11.743
‐ Oh, oh, William,
I don't think so.

56:11.743 --> 56:15.289
But just because
this is the first time

56:15.289 --> 56:17.499
doesn't mean
that it's the last.

56:17.499 --> 56:20.919
♪ ♪

56:20.919 --> 56:25.090
‐ Once a month, you could have
a fun weekend for yourself

56:25.090 --> 56:26.675
and you'd get to see
my big smile

56:26.675 --> 56:28.135
if it wouldn't
bother you too much.

56:28.135 --> 56:29.511
‐ [laughs]

56:29.511 --> 56:31.680
Oh, I don't think
seeing your smile

56:31.680 --> 56:32.764
would bother anyone.

56:32.764 --> 56:33.765
‐ [laughs]

56:33.765 --> 56:37.603
BETSY: [pained moaning]

56:37.603 --> 56:40.689
‐ I thought you said
it was working.

56:40.689 --> 56:42.524
BETSY: It was.

56:44.276 --> 56:46.028
I'll be right back.

56:47.738 --> 56:49.823
‐ There are many cases
where a higher dose

56:49.823 --> 56:52.200
loses its effectiveness
fairly quickly

56:52.200 --> 56:54.703
because the patient
develops a tolerance.

56:54.703 --> 56:57.706
BETSY: [retching]

56:57.706 --> 57:00.709
[tense percussive music]

57:00.709 --> 57:06.632
♪ ♪

57:06.632 --> 57:09.384
‐ [panting]

57:32.866 --> 57:36.078
[breathing heavily]

57:36.078 --> 57:38.163
PROFESSOR: This makes the user
increase their dose again

57:38.163 --> 57:39.539
at a fast rate.

57:39.539 --> 57:41.917
‐ And is that dangerous?

57:41.917 --> 57:43.126
‐ Absolutely.

57:43.126 --> 57:44.628
It's one of the reasons
why overdose rates

57:44.628 --> 57:46.672
are so much higher
on OxyContin.

57:46.672 --> 57:48.632
MICHAEL: These are
the new numbers,

57:48.632 --> 57:50.926
and you'll see
a significant difference

57:50.926 --> 57:53.053
from the initial
rollout figures.

57:59.601 --> 58:00.602
RICHARD: Better.

58:00.602 --> 58:01.812
‐ Really great job, Richie.

58:01.812 --> 58:03.146
‐ That's really great.

58:03.146 --> 58:05.899
‐ Yes, yes, there's
been a definite improvement

58:05.899 --> 58:08.193
in the sales figures.

58:08.193 --> 58:10.946
We also found doctors who
attended the weekend seminars

58:10.946 --> 58:13.281
have been writing
twice as many prescriptions

58:13.281 --> 58:15.075
as doctors who don't.

58:15.075 --> 58:18.495
‐ Then we should throw
more weekend seminars.

58:18.495 --> 58:23.041
‐ But, um, more significantly,
doubling the dose

58:23.041 --> 58:26.169
not only solved
the breakthrough pain issue,

58:26.169 --> 58:28.296
it increased our bottom line,

58:28.296 --> 58:31.466
since manufacturing
a 20 milligram or 40 milligram

58:31.466 --> 58:35.470
is almost the same cost
as a 10 milligram.

58:35.470 --> 58:37.139
This is bringing in revenue

58:37.139 --> 58:40.684
at a much faster rate
than projected.

58:40.684 --> 58:44.312
‐ There's a scenario
I've been concerned about.

58:44.312 --> 58:47.065
‐ And what is that,
my dear cousin?

58:47.065 --> 58:50.527
‐ Well, what happens if
someone has breakthrough pain

58:50.527 --> 58:53.321
and they're already
at 40 milligrams?

58:56.908 --> 59:00.245
‐ The sales reports from last
quarter were terrific,

59:00.245 --> 59:03.165
so much so that I am
pleased to announce

59:03.165 --> 59:06.835
that we will be launching
a brand‐new product.

59:06.835 --> 59:10.088
Ladies and gentlemen, it is
time to double the dose again

59:10.088 --> 59:14.176
as I present to you
the 80‐milligram pill.

59:14.176 --> 59:17.721
[applause]

59:17.721 --> 59:19.514
‐ Whoo!

